{
  "doc_id": "24403",
  "text": "The majority of the cases of DRSCT occur in the abdomen; however, many case reports have described this tumour originating from different organs such as testis, extremities, salivary glands, and brain [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Clinical presentation depends on the primary location of the tumour as well as disease stage. Diagnosis typically requires a tissue biopsy with identification of histopathological features along with immunohistochemistry and molecular testing. Fine-needle aspiration has also been used for the diagnosis of DRSCT [CITATION_5] . As previously mentioned, hallmark feature in molecular testing is the presence of WT1-EWS fusion; however, case reports with atypical molecular features have also been described [CITATION_6] .",
